caption: Bozu is known for their sushi bombs so thought we'd try it. I'd say the style can be called right in the midpoint of being casual to fancy sushi. I'd prefer more fish to the current rice ratio but sushi hits the spot every time as long as it's fresh!
I give them 10% tip and they complained that it's to low, automatic 1 star 🌟 I'm not obligated to tip you all.

We met with friends at this spot for dinner. This spot was recommended to us by a friend.  Well, it was very nice. The staff members welcomed us with a smile and we felt fantastic. The meal was great. We loved this place very much and we shall definitely come back again. we highly recommend this place.

This place is amazing! The seaweed salad was unlike any I have had before. Lots of hijiki this salad is more flavorful and full bodied. The salad is more dark green, with pink and white seaweed too. I'm used to the sweet, neon green seaweed salad from most sushi and poké planes. This was something very different.  The sushi bombs are just that, the bomb! (I know, sorry). A dab of rice with high quality fish or veggies on top. We ordered all the gluten free bombs along with gluten free spot sauce and I was in gluten free heaven. The bluefin toro was my favorite with the McLow and Mexican bombs just behind it.  Paired with a crisp fruity sake, I floated out on a Bozu cloud. So delicious and nutritious. You must needs eat from here

But for 8.50 I’d rather have a roll or some nigiri, the options were very limited and the quality was about average for the area. Lots of rice, lots of mayo for some reason. The vegetarian rolls were a disaster- we ordered three and they all had the same flavor/texture despite being different rolls. All had the same “mixed veggies” in them, like when you buy a bag of mixed veggies in the freezer section. Tons of mayo or cream cheese, not sure. We had to drown them in soy sauce to make them edible. I topped mine with smoked mussels I happened to have on hand just to give it some variety. Maybe the dine in experience is better??

We ordered from bozu at ~7pm, the eta for pickup was 730. We showed up at the restaurant at 745p and asked for a status. After about 10min of complete disorganization, they told us it would be about 10minutes. We waited patiently for 20min as we assumed they having trouble with the orders. We asked again 20min later, and they rudely told us to stop asking them and that it would be out in another 10 minutes. Being understanding and reasonable, we thoght they might be a bad day and decided to tolerate the slight disrespect towardsajd their loyal customer who supports them during quarantine. At approximately 845 (a full hour and 15minutes after the eta, they told us it would be another 15minutes. This is complete and utter disregard for our time and our loyalty. This is unacceptable, I would like a full refund and to write a review so all customers see what terrible service and manners this establishment displayed. We did not receive our food and left. We will not be returning.

(Translated by Google) Good food lousy service. The first day I went everything went well, the second time we were touched by a waitress who served our dish at the next table. The people at this table ate a few servings of the plate (2/7 units) and returned it saying it was not theirs. Then they served us, and when we told him that there was less quantity in this ration (5/7 units) he assured us that it was the one they served. Seeing this, we told him to give us the letter to check it ... and he stayed silent for a few seconds and then said that they had finished in the kitchen and that they had no more. After sitting at 6 at a table of 4, bringing food started from another table and lying to our faces, they brought us the tip included in the bill ... Fantastic.  (Original) Buena comida servicio pésimo. El primer día que fui todo fue bien, la segunda vez nos tocó una camarera que sirvió un plato nuestro en la mesa de al lado. La gente de esta mesa se comió unas cuántas porciones del plato (2/7 unidades) y lo devolvió diciendo que no era suyo. Acto seguido nos lo sirvieron a nosotros, y cuando le dijimos que había menos cantidad en esta ración (5/7 unidades) nos aseguró que era la que servían. Viendo esto, le dijimos que nos diera la carta para comprobarlo.....y se quedó unos segundos callada para luego decir que se habían acabado en cocina y que no les quedaban más. Tras sentarnos a 6 en una mesa de 4, traernos comida empezada de otra mesa y mentirnos a la cara, nos trajeron la propina incluida en la factura... Fantástico.

It was the eve of a first spring night before what will hopefully be the last snow of 2018. Looking for a new restaurant that would suit our specificites, we connected with our chef de cuisine in Berlin, who recommended Bozu.  The anticipation of the evening neared as we took the L all the way to Bedford, tunneling under the East River at what truly felt was a record pace. Just a few blocks from the station is Bozu. Humble from the exterior, but playful and sophisticated from the moment you step in. With the warm air that flowed as we escaped the chill, Bosu set an expectation for a culinary experience that we won't soon forget.  We are seated at the bar. Far right to be specific. Secluded from view but available to view the scene at our leisure. The bar tender was friendly and to the point. We were welcome to order as we pleased.  We decided on the miso soup, the Bozu salad and another app of which the name escapes me. Additionally we received 3 sushi bombs and 2 rolls. Also had an aged sake and a pudding for dessert.  The food came out like a dance. With each dish we finished, the new dish came out in perfect harmony. The food was delicious, and the fish was amongst the freshest we have ever tasted. By the end of the meal, we were satisfied, only to find ourselves back on the L train shortly after, anticipating our next return to Bozu.

This is a cozy restaurant in Williamsburg. We decided to head there early knowing going later meant long wait time.  I guess the main feature would be the Daruma dolls hanging at the entrance. The open kitchen and seating around the bar and table seating.  It was a cozy, not overly loud and nice lighting. Our server was quick and polite. We started with a  cocktails which looked interesting.  I wanted to to try the rambutan cocktail while my friend went for the sake recommended by the server. We did the pork bell, fried chicken and the fried octopus balls. We decided to share some of their sushi 'bombs'. We tried the  The drink was quite good and my friend was very happy with the recommended sake. I really liked their take on fried chicken. It was crispy and moist on the inside. Not oily at all. I liked the pork belly but maybe it is my Asian roots but it would have been better with rice. LOL  The sushi bombs were a bite size morsel of goodness. The flavors on point. I really liked the Mexican one as well as the Tuna. The is one restaurant that you can keep coming back too. Friendly service. Excellent food in a nice laid back atmosphere. In the warmer months the terrace is probably quite nice but for us it was closed.

Our waitress was rude and kept repeatedly suggesting that we should get drinks (which I agree we should have) but it was 5pm and we had a long night ahead for our bachelorette. Portion sizes we hard to guess at so we ordered a few items at a time and her face soured each round.  With our last roll she just brought our check though no one requested it. Odd.  Oh well.  Ill be back to sit at the better lit sushi bar and to add my own doodles to those menu binders.

Great hipster joint.  I call it hipster because it's in a hipster area.  They always know of the best places to eat.  This little gem had delicious sushi party bombs and pork betty that melted in my mouth.  I'd stay away from the regular sushi though; it was flavorless and not worth the moola.  It can get expensive; I paid $80 for my share of the meal.  That's what you get for eating with someone who's always freaking hungry no matter what he's already eaten!
Great food and drinks...great service and good price for the experience
This is one of the best spots in the neighborhood, and definitely among the best Japanese restaurants in brooklyn. Sister restaurants Samurai Mama and One or Eight are also fantastic.
Good sushi place! A bit noisy in the main room.

This was the worst restaurant i've ever been to in New York. The service was horrible. It was so dark in there i couldn't even see the menu,and i felt very uncomfortable with way they treated me. Never again.

The ambiance at bozy was intimate and the servers were very friendly and attentive. We tried a few different sushi bombs. My favorite part was that they had three different types of wasibi-infused soy sauces! Note that they only accept cash or American express so be prepared!
The raw fish was all of supreme freshness.
Nice place
Chicken is awesome, so are the sushi bombs. Great Sushi in Williamsburg.
try the bombs they are awsome
Octoballs. Noodle dishes are fantastic. Small plates are really small and not very filling but great to try interesting new flavors and share.
Phenomenal sushi and cocktails. Like no other.
Really interesting Japanese food.

One of the most fun and interesting looking restaurants I've ever been to. It's like a dream-space, with each section of the restaurant different than the others, so you can kind of curate your experience by where you sit. Always crowded but never too loud, probably because it's a long narrow room, rather than a big square one.  Food is incredibly good, but it's quite expensive.  It's got that amazing service you can expect from a japanese restaurant.
I love this place. Beautiful restaurant. Original food. Nice people.
